<h1 id="2-fast">2. <a href="https://fast.com/">Fast</a></h1>

<p>Fast is an open source CLI utility developed by Netflixâ€™s fast.com service and you can also access it directly from the browser.</p>

<p>Fast is the perfect tool for those who just want to check the download speed in a very simple way.</p>

<p>To use it via the command line you will need <code class="highlighter-rouge">npm</code> properly installed on your system and then run command:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span class="nb">sudo </span>npm <span class="nb">install</span> <span class="nt">--global</span> fast-cli</code></pre></figure>

<p>You can also install it using the snap:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span class="nb">sudo </span>snap <span class="nb">install </span>fast</code></pre></figure>

<p>After installed you can run via command line:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">fast</code></pre></figure>

<p><img src="/assets/img/commands/fast.gif" alt="Fast" /></p>

<hr />

<h1 id="3-libretest">3. <a href="https://librespeed.org/">LibreTest</a></h1>
<p>LibreTest is open source and does not use Flash, Java and Websocket. It can be accessed directly by the browser and used via the command line according to additional tools that implement it.</p>

<p>Its differential is that you can use it on your server and offer as a service and use curl via the command line pointing to your server (this procedure is outside the scope of this article).</p>

<p><img src="/assets/img/commands/libretest.gif" alt="LibreTest" /></p>

